SIMPLE: thin
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thin
<hw>Thin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Thiner</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Thinest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>thinne</ets>,
<ets>thenne</ets>, <ets>thunne</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ynne</ets>; akin
to D. <ets>dun</ets>, G. <ets>d⟦uum⟧nn</ets>, OHG. <ets>dunni</ets>,
Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧unnr</ets>, Sw. <ets>tunn</ets>, Dan. <ets>tynd</ets>,
Gael. & Ir. <ets>tana</ets>, W. <ets>teneu</ets>, L. <ets>tenuis</ets>,
Gr. <?/ (in comp.) stretched out, <?/ stretched, stretched out, long,
Skr. <ets>tanu</ets> thin, slender; also to AS. <ets><?/enian</ets> to
extend, G. <ets>dehnen</ets>, Icel. <ets><?/enja</ets>, Goth.
<ets><?/anjan</ets> (in comp.), L. <ets>tendere</ets> to stretch,
<ets>tenere</ets> to hold, Gr. <?/ to stretch, Skr. <ets>tan</ets>.
⟦root⟧51 & 237. Cf. <er>Attenuate</er>, <er>Dance</er>, <er>Tempt</er>,
<er>Tenable</er>, <er>Tend</er> to move, <er>Tenous</er>,
<er>Thunder</er>, <er>Tone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having little
thickness or extent from one surface to its opposite; <as>as, a
<ex>thin</ex> plate of metal; <ex>thin</ex> paper; a <ex>thin</ex>
board; a <ex>thin</ex> covering.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rare; not dense or thick; -- applied to fluids or
soft mixtures; <as>as, <ex>thin</ex> blood; <ex>thin</ex> broth;
<ex>thin</ex> air</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the day, when the air is more <qex>thin</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Satan, bowing low⟦br⟧
His gray dissimulation, disappeared,⟦br⟧
Into <qex>thin</qex> air diffused.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not close; not crowded; not filling the space; not
having the individuals of which the thing is composed in a close or
compact state; hence, not abundant; <as>as, the trees of a forest are
<ex>thin</ex>; the corn or grass is <ex>thin</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ferrara is very large, but extremely <qex>thin</qex> of
people.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not full or well grown; wanting in
plumpness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seven <qex>thin</qex> ears . . . blasted with the east wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xli. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Not stout; slim; slender; lean; gaunt; <as>as, a
person becomes <ex>thin</ex> by disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Wanting in body or volume; small; feeble; not
full.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Thin</qex>, hollow sounds, and lamentable screams.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Slight; small; slender; flimsy; wanting substance or
depth or force; superficial; inadequate; not sufficient for a covering;
<as>as, a <ex>thin</ex> disguise</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My tale is done, for my wit is but <qex>thin</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Thin</ex> is used in the formation of compounds
which are mostly self-explaining; as, <ex>thin</ex>-faced,
<ex>thin</ex>-lipped, <ex>thin</ex>-peopled, <ex>thin</ex>-shelled, and
the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Thin section</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Section</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thin
<hw>Thin</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Not thickly or closely; in a
seattered state; <as>as, seed sown <ex>thin</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Spain is <qex>thin</qex> sown of people.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thin
<hw>Thin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thinned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thinning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS.
ge<ets>⟦thorn⟧ynnian</ets>.]</ety> <def>To make thin (in any of the
senses of the adjective).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Thin
<hw>Thin</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow or become thin; -- used
with some adverbs, as <xex>out</xex>, <xex>away</xex>, etc.; <as>as,
geological strata <ex>thin</ex> out, <it>i. e.</it>, gradually diminish
in thickness until they disappear</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thine</ent>⟦br⟧
